analysis: The documents primarily focus on establishing and modifying wildlife refuges and breeding grounds, mainly for migratory birds, across various states in the United States. These refuges are created on lands owned or controlled by the U.S. government, often under the jurisdiction of the Department of Agriculture or the Department of the Interior. The orders specify the land areas, often described by legal subdivisions (sections, townships, ranges, and meridians). A common theme is the prohibition of hunting, trapping, or disturbing wildlife within the refuge boundaries, with exceptions made under specific regulations. Some orders modify existing refuges, either by adding land or changing the administering department. The purpose is consistently to conserve and protect wildlife, particularly migratory birds.
title: Wildlife Refuge Land Reservations
